<div id="review_478725922" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/478725922" />
    <a title="John" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8220634-john"><img alt="John" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1551632307p2/8220634.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/478725922?book_show_action=true">Dec 16, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John" href="/user/show/8220634-john">John</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8220634-john?shelf=2013">2013</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8220634-john?shelf=biography">biography</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer478725922" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14532009698745123464">Short, succint, insightful -- an unlikely biography of a great writer by a great writer, with the appropriate emphasis on the man&apos;s literary output as a product of his curious Life (and not, thankfully, the other way around). <br/><br/>Interesting to see how much Yourcenar and Mishima are alike and unlike, and where the two converge, against a literary landscape of excess, dramatism, post-war Japan, and an odd attraction to the idea of suicide -- very present in the works of both authors.<br/><br/>On a personal not</span>
  <span id="freeText14532009698745123464" style="display:none">Short, succint, insightful -- an unlikely biography of a great writer by a great writer, with the appropriate emphasis on the man's literary output as a product of his curious Life (and not, thankfully, the other way around). <br /><br />Interesting to see how much Yourcenar and Mishima are alike and unlike, and where the two converge, against a literary landscape of excess, dramatism, post-war Japan, and an odd attraction to the idea of suicide -- very present in the works of both authors.<br /><br />On a personal note, I expected a longer, more detailed account of Mishima's character and Life, but was positively surprised by how the somewhat abrupt (albeit expected) ending makes the work be something more.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14532009698745123464" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


